t means that feature was genuinely important. This \nis more reliable than tree based importance since it directly measures \nimpact on model performance rather than split counts.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"### 2.5 SHAP Values","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"explainer = shap.TreeExplainer(rf)\nshap_values = explainer.shap_values(X)\n\nplt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))\nshap.summary_plot(shap_values, X, plot_type=\"bar\", show=False)\nplt.title(\"SHAP — Mean Feature Importance Across All Classes\")\nplt.tight_layout()\nplt.show()","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-03-31T11:29:07.776822Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-03-31T11:29:07.777301Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-03-31T11:29:25.279180Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-03-31T11:29:07.777271Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-03-31T11:29:25.278043Z"}},"outputs":[{"output_type":"display_data","data":{"text/plain":"<Figure size 800x950 with 1 Axes>","image/png":"\n"},"metadata":{}}],"execution_count":8},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"SHAP (SHapley Additive exPlanations) assigns each feature an importance score \nbased on game theory. It measures the contribution of each feature to every \nindividual prediction. Unlike other methods SHAP is both globally and locally \ninterpretable — it tells us not just which features matter overall but how \nmuch each feature pushed a specific prediction in a particular direction. \nIt is considered the most reliable and explainable feature importance method.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"## 3. Create New Meaningful Features\n\nBased on the feature importance results above we now engineer new features \nthat capture relationships between existing dimensions. These new features \naim to improve the model's ability to differentiate between career categories.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# Hardcode originals — never use filter after new cols exist\nriasec_cols_orig = ['RIASEC_Artistic', 'RIASEC_Conventional', 'RIASEC_Enterprising',\n                    'RIASEC_Investigative', 'RIASEC_Realistic', 'RIASEC_Social']\n\n# Drop if already exist from previous runs\nfor col in ['RIASEC_Spread', 'IC_Index', 'Leadership_Social_Score']:\n    if col in df.columns:\n        df.drop(columns=[col], inplace=True)\n\n# Now create cleanly\ndf['RIASEC_Spread'] = df[riasec_cols_orig].max(axis=1) - df[riasec_cols_orig].min(axis=1)\ndf['IC_Index'] = df['RIASEC_Investigative'] + df['RIASEC_Conventional']\ndf['Leadership_Social_Score'] = (df['WS_Leadership'] +\n                                  df['RIASEC_Social'] +\n                                  df['RIASEC_Enterprising'])\n\nnew_features = ['RIASEC_Spread', 'IC_Index', 'Leadership_Social_Score']\n\nprint(\"New features created cleanly!\")\nprint(df[new_features].describe().round(3))","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-03-31T11:29:25.280606Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-03-31T11:29:25.281173Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-03-31T11:29:25.306089Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-03-31T11:29:25.281133Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-03-31T11:29:25.304902Z"}},"outputs":[{"name":"stdout","text":"New features created cleanly!\n       RIASEC_Spread  IC_Index  Leadership_Social_Score\ncount        873.000   873.000                  873.000\nmean           0.817     0.924                    1.198\nstd            0.142     0.323                    0.547\nmin            0.308     0.067                    0.190\n25%            0.717     0.668                    0.709\n50%            0.825     0.911                    1.140\n75%            0.948     1.186                    1.652\nmax            1.000     1.761                    2.768\n","output_type":"stream"}],"execution_count":9},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"We engineered 8 new features, each targeting a specific weakness in the \nraw feature set:\n\n- **RIASEC_Spread** — difference between max and min RIASEC score. A high \nspread means very focused interests pointing clearly toward one career cluster. \nA low spread means broad interests with no strong direction.\n\n- **IC_Index** — sum of Investigative and Conventional scores. Confirmed by \nall 5 importance algorithms as the two strongest predictors of tech careers \n(Computer/IT, Engineering, Science). This composite amplifies that signal.\n\n- **Leadership_Social_Score** — Leadership work style combined with Social \nand Enterprising RIASEC scores. A strong composite predictor for Management, \nBusiness/Finance and Sales career categories.\n\n","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"## 4. LightGBM Performance to measure the Before vs After New Features","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"from sklearn.model_selection import cross_val_score\n\nX_before = df[feature_cols]\nscores_before = cross_val_score(\n    lgb.LGBMClassifier(random_state=42, verbose=-1),\n    X_before, y, cv=5, scoring='accuracy'\n)\n\nX_after = df[feature_cols + new_features]\nscores_after = cross_val_score(\n    lgb.LGBMClassifier(random_state=42, verbose=-1),\n    X_after, y, cv=5, scoring='accuracy'\n)\n\nprint(\"=== LightGBM Performance Comparison ===\")\nprint(f\"\\nBefore new features: {scores_before.mean():.4f} (+/- {scores_before.std():.4f})\")\nprint(f\"After new features:  {scores_after.mean():.4f} (+/- {scores_after.std():.4f})\")\nprint(f\"\\nImprovement: {(scores_after.mean() - scores_before.mean())*100:.2f}%\")\n\nplt.figure(figsize=(8, 5))\nplt.bar(['Before\\n(28 features)', 'After\\n(31 features)'],\n        [scores_before.mean(), scores_after.mean()],\n        color=['#534AB7', '#1D9E75'], width=0.4)\nplt.ylabel(\"Cross Validation Accuracy\")\nplt.title(\"LightGBM Accuracy — Before vs After Feature Engineering\")\nplt.ylim(0.5, 1.0)\nfor i, v in enumerate([scores_before.mean(), scores_after.mean()]):\n    plt.text(i, v + 0.01, f'{v:.4f}', ha='center', fontweight='bold')\nplt.tight_layout()\nplt.show()","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-03-31T11:29:25.307405Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-03-31T11:29:25.308043Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-03-31T11:29:44.186103Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-03-31T11:29:25.307887Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-03-31T11:29:44.185004Z"}},"outputs":[{"name":"stdout","text":"=== LightGBM Performance Comparison ===\n\nBefore new features: 0.5851 (+/- 0.0818)\nAfter new features:  0.5943 (+/- 0.0879)\n\nImprovement: 0.91%\n","output_type":"stream"},{"output_type":"display_data","data":{"text/plain":"<Figure size 800x500 with 1 Axes>","image/png":"\n"},"metadata":{}}],"execution_count":10},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"We use 5-fold cross validation to fairly compare model performance before \nand after adding the engineered features. Cross validation splits the data \ninto 5 parts, trains on 4 and tests on 1 each time, giving a more reliable \naccuracy estimate than a single train-test split. An improvement in accuracy \nafter adding new features confirms that our engineered features carry genuine \npredictive signal.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"## 5. Drop Weak Original Features\n\nBased on the feature importance plot we identify a clear gap in importance \nscores. Features above the gap contribute meaningful signal while features \nbelow the gap add noise. We use this natural cutoff to decide which features \nto drop.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# Check importance of original features using LightGBM\nlgbm2 = lgb.LGBMClassifier(random_state=42, verbose=-1)\nlgbm2.fit(df[feature_cols + new_features], y)\n\nimportance_df = pd.DataFrame({\n    'Feature': feature_cols + new_features,\n    'Importance': lgbm2.feature_importances_\n}).sort_values('Importance', ascending=False)\n\nprint(importance_df.to_string())\nprint(f\"\\nFeatures with zero importance: {importance_df[importance_df['Importance']==0]['Feature'].tolist()}\")\n\n# Plot\nplt.figure(figsize=(12, 10))\nsns.barplot(data=importance_df, x='Importance', y='Feature', palette='viridis')\nplt.title(\"Feature Importance — Full Feature Set (Original + Engineered)\")\nplt.tight_layout()\nplt.show()","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-03-31T11:29:44.187519Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-03-31T11:29:44.187874Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-03-31T11:29:46.921386Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-03-31T11:29:44.187843Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-03-31T11:29:46.920379Z"}},"outputs":[{"name":"stdout","text":"                        Feature  Importance\n5                 RIASEC_Social        3001\n3          RIASEC_Investigative        2797\n4              RIASEC_Realistic        2723\n28                RIASEC_Spread        2436\n2           RIASEC_Enterprising        2355\n29                     IC_Index        2269\n1           RIASEC_Conventional        2255\n0               RIASEC_Artistic        1889\n30      Leadership_Social_Score        1685\n10        WS_Concern for Others        1656\n9        WS_Attention to Detail        1589\n16                 WS_Integrity        1521\n17                WS_Leadership        1477\n8        WS_Analytical Thinking        1444\n13              WS_Independence        1396\n15                WS_Innovation        1264\n20        WS_Social Orientation        1240\n6         WS_Achievement/Effort        1217\n27        WV_Working Conditions        1161\n21          WS_Stress Tolerance        1155\n11               WS_Cooperation        1135\n19              WS_Self-Control        1101\n12             WS_Dependability        1081\n26                   WV_Support         992\n14                WS_Initiative         947\n18               WS_Persistence         947\n7   WS_Adaptability/Flexibility         946\n23              WV_Independence         817\n25             WV_Relationships         693\n22               WV_Achievement         685\n24               WV_Recognition         667\n\nFeatures with zero importance: []\n","output_type":"stream"},{"output_type":"display_data","data":{"text/plain":"<Figure size 1200x1000 with 1 Axes>","image/png":"\n"},"metadata":{}}],"execution_count":11},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"We check importance of all features including the 3 new ones to identify \nwhich original features have zero or near-zero importance. Features with \nzero importance contribute nothing to the model and can be safely dropped \nto reduce noise and improve generalization.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"### We are checking the weakest features by importance in the tail","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"print(importance_df.tail(10).to_string())","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-03-31T11:29:46.922641Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-03-31T11:29:46.923567Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-03-31T11:29:46.930578Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-03-31T11:29:46.923528Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-03-31T11:29:46.929699Z"}},"outputs":[{"name":"stdout","text":"                        Feature  Importance\n19              WS_Self-Control        1101\n12             WS_Dependability        1081\n26                   WV_Support         992\n14                WS_Initiative         947\n18               WS_Persistence         947\n7   WS_Adaptability/Flexibility         946\n23              WV_Independence         817\n25             WV_Relationships         693\n22               WV_Achievement         685\n24               WV_Recognition         667\n","output_type":"stream"}],"execution_count":12},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"A clear importance gap was found between `WS_Adaptability/Flexibility` (946) \nand the bottom 4 Work Values which all score below 820. This gap indicates \nthese 4 Work Value features contribute significantly less signal than all \nother features. \n# Feature Dropping Decision: \n### \"Because after dropping the 4 features I was having tha drop in my accuracy by -1.94% ... so it was a clear message that I should reatin all original features because all features are contributing to the accuracy\" ","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"## 6. Standardization of New Engineered Features\n\nOur original 28 features were already scaled to 0 to 1 in Phase 2 using \nMinMaxScaler. However our 3 newly engineered features were created by \ncombining those scaled features and may have different ranges. We need \nto scale them to match the same 0 to 1 range.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"from sklearn.preprocessing import MinMaxScaler\n\n# Check ranges of new features before scaling\nprint(\"=== Ranges BEFORE scaling ===\")\nprint(df[new_features].describe().loc[['min', 'max']].round(4))\n\n# Scale only the 3 new engineered features\nscaler = MinMaxScaler()\ndf[new_features] = scaler.fit_transform(df[new_features])\n\n# Verify\nprint(\"\\n=== Ranges AFTER scaling ===\")\nprint(df[new_features].describe().loc[['min', 'max']].round(4))\n\nprint(\"\\nAll features now on same 0 to 1 scale!\")","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-03-31T11:29:46.931811Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-03-31T11:29:46.932197Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-03-31T11:29:46.972392Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-03-31T11:29:46.932169Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-03-31T11:29:46.971412Z"}},"outputs":[{"name":"stdout","text":"=== Ranges BEFORE scaling ===\n     RIASEC_Spread  IC_Index  Leadership_Social_Score\nmin          0.308    0.0667                   0.1898\nmax          1.000    1.7607                   2.7685\n\n=== Ranges AFTER scaling ===\n     RIASEC_Spread  IC_Index  Leadership_Social_Score\nmin            0.0       0.0                      0.0\nmax            1.0       1.0                      1.0\n\nAll features now on same 0 to 1 scale!\n","output_type":"stream"}],"execution_count":13},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"The 3 engineered features were on different ranges since they are sums and \ndifferences of the original scaled features. For example IC_Index was the \nsum of two 0 to 1 features giving a range of 0 to 2. MinMaxScaler brings \nall 3 new features to the same 0 to 1 range as the original features \nensuring no single feature dominates distance calculations in our \nrecommendation model.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"## 7. KMeans Clustering — New Feature Creation\n\nAs required in Phase 3 we explore whether KMeans clustering can generate \na meaningful new feature. We cluster occupations based on their RIASEC \nprofiles and add the cluster label as a new categorical feature.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"from sklearn.metrics import silhouette_score\n\nriasec_cols_orig = ['RIASEC_Artistic', 'RIASEC_Conventional', 'RIASEC_Enterprising',\n                    'RIASEC_Investigative', 'RIASEC_Realistic', 'RIASEC_Social']\n\n# Find optimal K using silhouette score\nsilhouette_scores = []\nK_range = range(2, 10)\n\nfor k in K_range:\n    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=k, random_state=42, n_init=10)\n    labels = kmeans.fit_predict(df[riasec_cols_orig])\n    score = silhouette_score(df[riasec_cols_orig], labels)\n    silhouette_scores.append(score)\n    print(f\"K={k}: silhouette score = {score:.4f}\")\n\n# Plot\nplt.figure(figsize=(10, 4))\nplt.plot(K_range, silhouette_scores, marker='o', color='#534AB7', linewidth=2)\nplt.title(\"KMeans Silhouette Scores — Finding Optimal K\")\nplt.xlabel(\"Number of Clusters (K)\")\nplt.ylabel(\"Silhouette Score\")\nplt.xticks(K_range)\nplt.tight_layout()\nplt.show()\n\nbest_k = K_range[silhouette_scores.index(max(silhouette_scores))]\nprint(f\"\\nBest K: {best_k}\")","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-03-31T11:29:46.973606Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-03-31T11:29:46.974332Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-03-31T11:29:48.067521Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-03-31T11:29:46.974274Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-03-31T11:29:48.065889Z"}},"outputs":[{"name":"stdout","text":"K=2: silhouette score = 0.3331\nK=3: silhouette score = 0.3636\nK=4: silhouette score = 0.3559\nK=5: silhouette score = 0.3762\nK=6: silhouette score = 0.3516\nK=7: silhouette score = 0.3510\nK=8: silhouette score = 0.3303\nK=9: silhouette score = 0.3298\n","output_type":"stream"},{"output_type":"display_data","data":{"text/plain":"<Figure size 1000x400 with 1 Axes>","image/png":"\n"},"metadata":{}},{"name":"stdout","text":"\nBest K: 5\n","output_type":"stream"}],"execution_count":14},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"### Apply KMeans with Optimal K=5","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"kmeans_final = KMeans(n_clusters=best_k, random_state=42, n_init=10)\ndf['RIASEC_Cluster'] = kmeans_final.fit_predict(df[riasec_cols_orig])\nprint(f\"RIASEC_Cluster created! Distribution: {pd.Series(df['RIASEC_Cluster']).value_counts().to_dict()}\")\n\n\nfinal_feature_cols = feature_cols + new_features\n\n# Test if cluster feature improves model\nfinal_with_cluster = final_feature_cols + ['RIASEC_Cluster']\nscores_cluster = cross_val_score(\n    lgb.LGBMClassifier(random_state=42, verbose=-1),\n    df[final_with_cluster], y, cv=5, scoring='accuracy'\n)\n\nprint(f\"Baseline:                {scores_before.mean():.4f}\")\nprint(f\"With new features:       {scores_after.mean():.4f}\")\nprint(f\"With cluster added:      {scores_cluster.mean():.4f}\")\nprint(f\"Improvement vs baseline: {(scores_cluster.mean()-scores_before.mean())*100:+.2f}%\")","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-03-31T11:55:36.050012Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-03-31T11:55:36.050393Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-03-31T11:55:45.576728Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-03-31T11:55:36.050364Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-03-31T11:55:45.575788Z"}},"outputs":[{"name":"stdout","text":"RIASEC_Cluster created! Distribution: {1: 300, 4: 212, 3: 174, 2: 146, 0: 41}\nBaseline:                0.5851\nWith new features:       0.5943\nWith cluster added:      0.5943\nImprovement vs baseline: +0.92%\n","output_type":"stream"}],"execution_count":19},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# Final confirmed feature set\nfinal_feature_cols = feature_cols + new_features + ['RIASEC_Cluster']\n\nprint(\"=== Final Feature Set ===\")\nprint(f\"Original features:     {len(feature_cols)}\")\nprint(f\"Engineered features:   {len(new_features)}\")\nprint(f\"KMeans cluster:        1\")\nprint(f\"Total:                 {len(final_feature_cols)}\")\nprint(f\"\\nFinal accuracy:        {scores_cluster.mean():.4f}\")\nprint(f\"Improvement:           {(scores_cluster.mean()-scores_before.mean())*100:+.2f}%\")","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-03-31T11:55:58.066675Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-03-31T11:55:58.067710Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-03-31T11:55:58.075512Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-03-31T11:55:58.067653Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-03-31T11:55:58.074017Z"}},"outputs":[{"name":"stdout","text":"=== Final Feature Set ===\nOriginal features:     28\nEngineered features:   3\nKMeans cluster:        1\nTotal:                 32\n\nFinal accuracy:        0.5943\nImprovement:           +0.92%\n","output_type":"stream"}],"execution_count":20},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"### KMeans Clustering — Decision","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"The RIASEC_Cluster feature produced 5 meaningful career personality groups \nthat align well with real career domains. Although it did not improve \naccuracy further it also did not hurt performance. We keep it as it adds \ninterpretability to our recommendation system and satisfies the requirement \nof exploring KMeans as a feature creation method.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"## 8. Save Final Dataset","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"df_final = df[['SOC_Code', 'Title', 'Category', 'Dominant_RIASEC'] + final_feature_cols]\n\ndf_final.to_csv('onet_phase3.csv', index=False)\n\nprint(\"Saved: onet_phase3.csv\")\nprint(f\"Shape: {df_final.shape}\")\nprint(f\"\\nFeature breakdown:\")\nprint(f\"  Origin